    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            <term>Key Takeaway:</term> Solving logarithmic equations often involves rewriting the equation in exponential form, which allows us to find the value of the variable. 
            This process relies on understanding the relationship between logarithms and exponents, and it is a fundamental skill for working with logarithmic functions.
        </p>
           <p>
             When solving logarithmic equations, it's important to remember that the argument of the logarithm must be positive. This is because the logarithm of a negative number or zero is undefined in the real number system.
          </p>
          <p>
             Additionally, when solving logarithmic equations, remember the basic properties of logarithims such as the
             product rule that is <m>\log_b(xy) = \log_b(x) + \log_b(y)</m>, the quotient rule that is <m>\log_b(x/y) = \log_b(x) - \log_b(y)</m>, and the power rule that is <m>\log_b(x^n) = n \cdot \log_b(x)</m>.
         </p>
    </insight> 

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Solve for x: <m>\log₂(x) = 3</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To solve the equation <m>\log₂(x) = 3</m>, first rewrite it in exponential form. 
                The logarithmic equation <m>\log_b(a) = c</m> is equivalent to the exponential equation <m>\b^c = a</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                In our case, you have <m>b = 2</m>, <m>c = 3</m>, and <m>a = x</m>. 
                Therefore, you can rewrite the equation as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>2^3 = x</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, calculate <m>2^3</m>, which is equal to 8. 
                Therefore, the solution to the equation is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = 8</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Solve for x: <m>\log₃(x + 1) = 2</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To solve the equation <m>\log₃(x + 1) = 2</m>, first rewrite it in exponential form. 
                The logarithmic equation <m>\log_b(a) = c</m> is equivalent to the exponential equation <m>\b^c = a</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                In our case, you have <m>b = 3</m>, <m>c = 2</m>, and <m>a = x + 1</m>. 
                Therefore, you can rewrite the equation as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>3^2 = x + 1</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, calculate <m>3^2</m>, which is equal to 9. 
                Therefore, the solution to the equation is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x + 1 = 9</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Subtracting 1 from both sides gives:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = 8</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Solve for x: <m>\log₄(x - 2) = 1</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To solve the equation <m>\log₄(x - 2) = 1</m>, first rewrite it in exponential form. 
                The logarithmic equation <m>\log_b(a) = c</m> is equivalent to the exponential equation <m>\b^c = a</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                In this case, you have <m>\b = 4</m>, <m>\c = 1</m>, and <m>\a = x - 2</m>. 
                Therefore, you can rewrite the equation as:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>4^1 = x - 2</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, calculate <m>4^1</m>, which is equal to 4. 
                Therefore, the solution to the equation is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x - 2 = 4</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Adding 2 to both sides gives:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = 6</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example> 

